e same time most controversial concepts of modern linguistics. With regard to English, it became especially controversial with the rise of the so-called "New Englishes," where reality is much more complex than the neat distinction into native and non-native speakers would make us believe. This volume reconstructs the coming-into-being of the English native speaker in the second half of the nineteenth century in order to probe into the origins of the problems surrounding the concept today. A corpus of texts which includes not only the classics of the nineteenth-century linguistic literature but also numerous lesser-known articles from periodical journals of the time is investigated by means of historical discourse analysis in order to retrace the production and reproduction of this particularly important linguistic ideology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnglish languagexEnglish-speaking countries. 0aEnglish languagexSocial aspectsx19th century. 0aEnglish languagexUsagex19th century. 0aEnglish languagexVariationx19th century. 0aEnglish languagey19th centuryxSocial aspects 0aEnglish languagey19th centuryxSocial aspects. 0aEnglish languagey19th centuryxUsage. 0aEnglish languagey19th centuryxVariation. 0aEnglish languagezEnglish-speaking countries. 0aHistorical linguisticsxEnglish-speaking countries. 0aHistorical linguistics. 4aEnglisch. 4aSoziolinguistik. 4aSprachgeschichte. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aApplied Linguistics.  aEnglish Studies.  aHistorical Linguistics.  aSociolinguistics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Linguistics and Semiotics  2000-2014 (EN)z978311023845708iTitle